Example R code notebook¶

Keagan DeLong¶

The notebook explores traffic at the Port of Los Angeles, inspiration for the project came from the highly publicized backlog of traffic in 2021.

The Data¶

This project will analyze a dataset from the Port of Los Angeles, particularly total twenty-foot units of cargo. The dataset contains values from Janurary 2000 - December 2020. The purpose of this analysis is to test a hypothesized claim that we can compare the patterns of cargo during the 2008 Economic Crisis to the current supply chain issues we are experiencing in 2021.

The data is subsetted into the years surrounding the economic crisis. We seek to find that a reasonable correlation exists between the two events such that the trends produced during the recovery years after 2008 can be a reliable way to model the future.

Data was retrived from the Port of Los Angeles's website. The data is freely available to anyone though I have compiled it into a single comma separated values document and changed the date to an recognized ISO date format. The data can be viewed here.

The first step in this analysis is importing nessessary packages to handle and interpret the data. The data was already cleaned and formatted in Microsoft Excel to simpify the process.

Here we load in the dataset and format the columns we want to analyze in the R timeseries format. Moreover, we insure that the dates are in an acceptable format for easy of data processing while maintaining an acceptable ISO format. In the timeseries we specify that the frequency of the data is formatted in 12 month increments form the year 2000.

In [ ]:
handler <- read.csv("pola-container-statistics-2000-2020.csv", header = T)
container_stats <- handler[1:8]
container_stats$Date <- as.Date(as.yearmon(container_stats$Date, "%Y-%m", frac = 1))
container_stats_ts <- ts(container_stats, start = 2000, frequency = 12)

Further more the first steps of analyzing the data is going to be to plot the whole dataset to visually inspect the data.

In [ ]:
options(repr.plot.width=14, repr.plot.height=6, repr.plot.res = 125)

The first subset of the dataset we want is going to be the columns that contains the total TEUs recorded. This column is the addition of the total imports and exports of cargo.

In [ ]:
total_teus <- ts(container_stats$Total.TEUs, start = 2000, frequency = 12)
ts.plot(total_teus, xlab = "Year",
 ylab = "TEUs",
 main = "Total TEUS from 2000-2020")
 abline(reg = lm(total_teus~time(total_teus)))

Featured on the plot are two red rectangles that represent the areas that we want to compare. And an average regression line. These contain the data points between the years of 2008-2011 and 2019-2020. For our purpose we want to analyze the 36 months that encapsulate the worst of the 2008 finanical crisis (crisis1), since 2021 figures have not yet been released we will be using a 24 month period from 2019-2020 to compare. When conducting the forecast we will use the 12 months after the 2008 crisis (2009-2010) as a training set to compare to our test of the 2021 forecast (crisis2). Also featured on the plot is an average line found using a simple linear regression.

Since we want to extract the trend from the data, not the values themselves we will scale the data between 0-1 and find the correlation coefficent. The correlation coefficent will give us insight into how related the two sets of data are. Correlation coefficents are scaled between -1 and 1. A coefficent of 0 indicated no correlation, 1 being a strong positive correlation and vice-versa for -1.

In [ ]:
cor(crisis1, crisis2)
0.541011298888554

Our correlation coeffienct is approximately 0.54. This tells us there is a moderate correlation between the two time periods. Later we will dermine if there is a forecasted patern that can maintain or outperform this correlation coefficent.

Forecasting¶

ARMA Forecast¶

For our forecast we want to build a auto-regressive moving average (ARMA) model of the data to make predictions with. Utilizing the auto.arima() we will build a ARMA model of the two time periods.

In [ ]:
AutoArimaTotal <- auto.arima(total_teus)
summary(AutoArimaTotal)

In [ ]:
total_arma <- arima(total_teus, order = c(0,1,1))
In [ ]:
ts.plot(total_teus, xlab = "Year",
 ylab = "TEUs",
 main = "Total TEUs 2000.1-2020.12")
total_arma_fit <- total_teus - residuals(total_arma)
points(total_arma_fit, type = "l", col = 2, lty = 2)
In [ ]:
checkresiduals(total_arma_fit)

Warning message in modeldf.default(object):
“Could not find appropriate degrees of freedom for this model.”
In [ ]:
autoplot(forecast(total_arma_fit, 36))
In [ ]:
teu_forecast <- forecast(total_arma_fit, 36)
lower_forecast <- as.data.frame(teu_forecast$lower)
upper_forecast <- as.data.frame(teu_forecast$upper)

forecast_df <- container_stats$Total.TEUs

upper95_ts <- ts(c(forecast_df, upper_forecast$`95%`), start = 2000, frequency = 12)
upper80_ts <- ts(c(forecast_df, upper_forecast$`80%`), start = 2000, frequency = 12)
lower80_ts <- ts(c(forecast_df, lower_forecast$`80%`), start = 2000, frequency = 12)
lower95_ts <- ts(c(forecast_df, lower_forecast$`95%`), start = 2000, frequency = 12)

Above we have illustrated that we found a reasonable forecasted distribution that can maintain the correlation coefficent.

In conclusion, the ARMA forecast validated that we can keep the correlation the same between the crisis of 2008 and 2020 meaning that it is reasonable to make predictions utilizing the trends in recovery years after 2008 in modeling the prospect of future cargo tonnage.
